@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place "Beadit" where you
want on your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. No other files
or Libraries are needed. However, the game requires a 68020(+)
Amiga with Workbench 2.0 or higher and it must have at least 8
colours.

                             How to play?

  The game is played on a game board of a certain size, with or
without empty spaces (the empty spaces are represented by small
square blocks). In each game board, 4 types of coloured tiles are
randomly placed. The idea is to link (or 'thread'), horizontally
and/or vertically, like beads, tiles of the same type.

  When you click on a tile, the game decides which order the links
will be placed; first toward the top, then, toward the right, then,
downward and finally, toward the left. A link is created if TWO
links have not already been made from the clicked tile. The same
thing applys to tiles that could be linked, as the following
examples show:

  B   A - A
      |   ?  <- Potential link
  A - A   A*

  B - B   C

  ...However:

  B   A - A
      |
  A - A   B
      x <----- No link here
  B   A*  C

Note: the letters 'A', 'B' and 'C' represent the game tiles, the
      links are represented by bars ('-' et '|') and the '*'
      symbols are the clicked tiles.

  The principal goal of the game is to link tiles of the same type
in the best possible way. And the more the tiles there are, the
better it is... 3 linked tiles will give 1 point, but 2 linked
tiles will give no points...

  When all tiles are linked together, the game board is completed.
If there are no isolated tiles, you may get a bonus... but only if
the number of double links (links between 3 tiles) is greater than
the number of end links (ends of a series of tiles linked together
or doublets). For example, let's suppose that you have created 16
double links and 12 end links, the bonus will be:

 (16 - 12) * 5  =  4 * 5 = 20 bonus points.

  One thing you must watch for, is to avoid as much as possible
isolating single tiles... as the number of these isolated tiles
adds up until it exceeds 10... at that point, the game will be
over.

  Some tiles might be placed in such a way that it is impossible to
link them all. In other words, some tiles will be isolated... it is
part of the game...!

  Have fun!

  You can quit the game by clicking on the game window's close
button or by pressing on the 'Esc' key.

